<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-09-22T09:10:39-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-09-22T09:10:39-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5581&amp;p=50782#p50782</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5581&amp;p=50782#p50782"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Video shows Mario sound effects made in a tracker]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5581&amp;p=50782#p50782"><![CDATA[
I'm guessing the "grow" sound was sequenced as shown, but I'd bet the "shrink/pipe" sound was done with hardware sweep.<br /><br />Comparison to homebrew: All the sound effects in LJ65 are sequenced, with columns for pitch (8 bits), duty (4 bits), and volume (4 bits). For example, the sound when a piece lands on the stack looks something like this:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">E-4 8 C<br />C-4 8 A<br />A-3 8 8<br />F#3 8 6<br />E-3 8 4<br />D-3 8 3<br />C#3 8 2<br />C-3 8 1<br /></div><br /><br />Does this belong in NES Music?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Tue Sep 22, 2009 9:10 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
